<h2>
    Introduction to Chum Salmon Fishing
</h2>
<p>
    Chum salmon, often referred to as "dog salmon" due to the canine-like teeth the males develop during spawning, are one of the five Pacific salmon species. Known for their strength and fighting ability, chum salmon offer an exciting challenge for anglers of all skill levels. While not as commercially prized as chinook or coho, chum are abundant, hard-hitting, and great fun to catch — especially on light tackle.
</p>
<p>
    They typically run later in the season than other species, with their peak in Oregon occurring during fall months. Their runs are characterized by high numbers and aggressive feeding behavior, which makes them ideal for those seeking a productive fishing experience. With their explosive strikes and energetic fights, chum salmon offer an unforgettable adventure.
</p>
